# First-Agent Harness Improvement Task

REVIEW REQUIRED: use this during the first agent session after HarnessForge
generates the harness. Replace or retire this task after the project accepts
the improved harness.

## Goal

Deepen this repo's harness beyond what static generation can know. Use the
generated structure as a starting point, then inspect the real repository to
improve guidance, readiness signals, checks, ownership, and review boundaries.

## Inputs

Start with `{{agent_file}}`, `docs/harness/README.md`, component inventory,
change contract, verification matrix, sensor registry, evidence log, security
boundary map, `feature_list.json`, `progress.md`, and `session-handoff.md`.

## Work

1. Confirm the generated harness matches the real repo shape.
2. Run a fresh-session test from repo files only: identify what the project is,
   how it is organized, how it starts, how it is verified, and what work is
   current.
3. Treat initialization as its own phase: confirm startup, one trustworthy
   verification path, progress visibility, and source-of-truth routing before
   unrelated feature work.
4. Improve omitted component, package, app, service, job, or docs-root
   boundaries.
5. Route specs, plans, work items, workflows, ADRs, release notes, localized
   docs, and project docs to their source of truth. If localized docs exist,
   identify the source-of-truth locale or canonical docs root first.
6. Improve verification guidance with repo-owned commands that maintainers can
   run locally and in CI.
7. Update the verification matrix, sensor registry, and evidence log with
   realistic checks, owners, review cadence, and retirement conditions.
8. Improve runtime and process observability notes so runtime signals show what
   happened and plans, contracts, rubrics, and evidence show why a change should
   be accepted.
9. Improve security boundary notes for secrets, credentials, permissions,
   deployment, data flows, external services, and cost-incurring tools.
10. Add source, applicability, and retirement notes for durable rules accepted
    into root instructions or harness docs.
11. Record uncertain project-specific assumptions as review-required notes until
    a maintainer accepts them.

## Boundaries

- Do not overwrite project-owned instructions unless the user explicitly asks
  for that change or passes force behavior.
- Do not run target commands until the repo has an approved verification route
  for that command.
- Do not add user-specific tool preferences, local research mandates, personal
  memory paths, MCP configs, or machine-specific absolute paths.
- Do not install dependencies, create autonomous workflows, push branches, open
  pull requests, rotate secrets, or change cloud resources unless explicitly
  requested.
- Do not treat structural audit score as proof of real-agent effectiveness.
- Do not mark features, roadmap items, or tasks passing from agent confidence
  alone. Behavior, verification, status, and evidence must agree.

## Acceptance

- Root instructions stay compact and route durable detail into `docs/harness/`.
- Component inventory names important boundaries known after review.
- The fresh-session test has answer sources for purpose, organization, startup,
  verification, and current work.
- The verification matrix identifies the smallest reliable checks.
- The sensor registry records owner, source, purpose, and retirement condition.
- Important failures say what failed, why the boundary matters, and where to
  repair.
- The evidence log records what was reviewed, what changed, what checks ran,
  and what still needs maintainer review.
- `progress.md` and `session-handoff.md` capture objective, blockers,
  verification evidence, and next step.
